where $E_{\text{vib}}(v=0)$ is the zero-point vibrational energy.

The zero-point vibrational energy is given by:

$$E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{1}{2}\hbar\omega_e - \frac{1}{4}\hbar\omega_e x_e$$

Or in wavenumber units (dividing by $hc$):

$$\frac{E_{\text{vib}}(v=0)}{hc} = \frac{1}{2}\frac{\nu_e}{c} - \frac{1}{4}\frac{\nu_e x_e}{c}$$

Given:
- $D_0 = 2.4287$ eV
- $\nu_e/c = 1405.65$ cm$^{-1}$
- $\nu_e x_e/c = 23.20$ cm$^{-1}$

First, calculate the zero-point energy in cm$^{-1}$:

$$\frac{E_{\text{vib}}(v=0)}{hc} = \frac{1}{2}(1405.65) - \frac{1}{4}(23.20)$$

$$= 702.825 - 5.80 = 697.025 \text{ cm}^{-1}$$

Now convert this to eV. Using the conversion factor: 1 eV = 8065.54 cm$^{-1}$

$$E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{697.025}{8065.54} = 0.086398 \text{ eV}$$

Therefore:

$$D_e = D_0 + E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = 2.4287 + 0.086398 = 2.514898 \text{ eV}$$

Rounding to appropriate significant figures (5 significant figures based on the given data):

$$D_e = 2.5149 \text{ eV}$$

